  "prompt": "What kind of first jobs do neuroscience majors tend to get?",
  "response": "Neuroscience majors graduate with a strong foundation in biology, psychology, chemistry, and research methods, which opens up a variety of entry-level job opportunities. Here are some common first jobs for neuroscience majors:\n\n1. **Research Assistant/Lab Technician**  \n   - Work in academic, clinical, or industry labs assisting with neuroscience-related research.\n   - Responsibilities may include data collection, analysis, and lab maintenance.\n\n2. **Clinical Research Coordinator**  \n   - Assist in organizing and managing clinical trials or research studies, often in hospitals or research institutions.\n   - Work with patients, collect data, and ensure compliance with research protocols.\n\n3. **Behavioral Health Technician**  \n   - Work in mental health or rehabilitation settings, assisting patients with behavioral and cognitive challenges.\n   - May involve implementing treatment plans and monitoring progress.\n\n4. **Pharmaceutical Sales Representative**  \n   - Promote and sell pharmaceutical or medical products to healthcare professionals.\n   - Leverage neuroscience knowledge to explain product benefits.\n\n5. **Science Writer/Communicator**  \n   - Write or edit content for scientific publications, healthcare companies, or media outlets.\n   - Translate complex neuroscience concepts for a general audience.\n\n6. **Neurodiagnostic Technician**  \n   - Conduct tests such as EEGs (electroencephalograms) to monitor brain activity in clinical settings.\n   - Work in hospitals or specialized clinics.\n\n7. **Mental Health Technician/Caseworker**  \n   - Provide support to individuals with mental health conditions in clinical or community settings.\n   - May involve counseling, crisis intervention, and resource coordination.\n\n8. **Health Educator**  \n   - Educate communities or organizations about brain health, mental wellness, or related topics.\n   - Work in nonprofits, schools, or public health organizations.\n\n9. **Data Analyst**  \n   - Analyze and interpret data from neuroscience studies or other research projects.\n   - Use statistical software and programming tools to draw insights.\n\n10. **Graduate School or Professional Programs**  \n    - Many neuroscience majors pursue advanced degrees in neuroscience, psychology, medicine, or related fields to further specialize their careers.\n\nThe specific job a neuroscience graduate lands often depends on their interests, skills, and additional experiences (e.g., internships, research projects). Flexibility and adaptability are key, as neuroscience is an interdisciplinary field with broad applications.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
